<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-03-11T07:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-03-11T07:00:00-05:00" n="212" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d212">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">851.5151/1754: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-03-11T12:00:00+00:00">March 11,
                                    1938—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received March 11—8:35 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>371. The Paris editor of the <hi rend="italic">New York Herald
                                    Tribune</hi>, commenting upon the report that Blum had acceded
                                to the Radical Socialist demand <pb facs="0277" n="269" xml:id="pg_269"/> for rejection of exchange control, added that
                                “a reliable source said last night pressure from the Treasury
                                Department in Washington had helped him to make up his mind”.</p>
                            <p>We have received inquiries regarding this story and have replied that
                                it is absurd.</p>
                            <p>There is no mention of the story in the French press.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>